      {
         "id": "SECTION_couting",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Counting\n\nWhen beginning the study of humanity's discoveries related to the universe, we saw that, using our bodies, we can begin counting with our hands (<htcite0>). As we continued the study, we observed that investigations by Dr. Francisco González A. Redondo *et al.* demonstrated that counting is a practice performed by humanity for at least 37,000 years (<htcite1>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "3874d1e8-0f76-4432-9ee2-d8c8c9dccf53",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
                     "page": "Couting",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "a4f22e25-5839-407f-a1aa-634521d52b42",
                     "text": "González Redondo, Francisco A., et al.",
                     "page": "pp. 180 - 181",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2010",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p class=\"desc\"><img id=\"img9\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img9', '0%')\" src=\"images/ResearchGate/Figura-9-Hueso-de-Lebombo.png\" class=\"imgcenter\"/><b>Figure 3</b>: Representation of baboon bone adorned with markings. This image, credited to Enrique Silván Pobes, is featured in the scholarly work of Francisco A. Gonzáles Redondo et al.<br />The original is available in ResearchNet (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('adaed4fb-9c50-4ef9-ab79-c65f3c0629b8'); return false;\">González Redondo, Francisco A., et al., <htdate0></a>), and its inclusion here is made possible by the authorization of Doctor Francisco A. Gonzales Redondo.</p><p>Over the centuries, various numeration systems have been utilized, some of which endure to this day. In the following sections, we present an overview of contemporary systems alongside those that have recently fallen out of use.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2010",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "The chapter on counting (* The journey into numbers*) continued by demonstrating that numbers can always be added to other numbers, with no rule preventing this process.\n\nGiven this scenario, mathematicians developed, over the last centuries, the concept of limits, which was also introduced in the first chapter. Using this concept, we learned that when it is not possible to express a quantity through a specific value, we can say we are tending to that value. We also learned that, as numbers grow without end, we can say they tend to infinity (∞) (<htcite0>).",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "18a901e4-3da3-45d8-a239-fb551e78698e",
                     "text": "History Tracers Team",
